[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(21-24) This short section, concerning other Hezronites than those of the house of Caleb, is a parenthesis relating to a Hezronite element in Manassite Gilead.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(21) And afterward Hezron went in to the daughter of Machir.—This appears to mean, after the birth of the three sons mentioned in 1Chronicles 2:9.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(21) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And afterward Hezron went in to the daughter of Machir.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—This appears to mean, after the birth of the three sons mentioned in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 2:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Machir.—The firstborn of Manasseh (Genesis 1:23), to whom Moses gave the land of Gilead (Numbers 32:40; Deuteronomy 3:15). This explains the term “father of Gilead.” The great clan of Machir was the ruling clan in Gilead. Comp. Numbers 26:28, which mentions the clan of the Machirites, and adds that “Machir begat Gilead,” which perhaps means to say that the Israelite settlers in Gilead were of the clan Machir.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Machir.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The firstborn of Manasseh (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 1:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), to whom Moses gave the land of Gilead (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 32:40",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 3:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). This explains the term “father of Gilead.” The great clan of Machir was the ruling clan in Gilead. Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Numbers 26:28",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", which mentions the clan of the Machirites, and adds that “Machir begat Gilead,” which perhaps means to say that the Israelite settlers in Gilead were of the clan Machir.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Whom he married when he was threescore.—It is possible to see here a metaphorical statement of the fact that a branch of Hezronites amalgamated with the Machirites of Gilead. The “daughter of Machir” would then mean the clan so named. Comp. the expressions, “daughter of Zion” (Isaiah 37:22), “daughter of Judah” (Lamentations 1:15), “daughter of Babylon” (Isaiah 47:1).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Whom he married when he was threescore.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—It is possible to see here a metaphorical statement of the fact that a branch of Hezronites amalgamated with the Machirites of Gilead. The “daughter of Machir” would then mean the clan so named. Comp. the expressions, “daughter of Zion” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 37:22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), “daughter of Judah” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Lamentations 1:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), “daughter of Babylon” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 47:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The father of Gilead — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It is doubtful whether the word Gilead is here the name of a man, or of the country so called: if it be the latter, the expression means, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the prince of Gilead, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "as the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "father ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "often signifies: if the former, the Gilead intended must have been a person of noted valour, probably the great champion in those parts.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "2:1-55 Genealogies. - We are now come to the register of the children of Israel, that distinguished people, who were to dwell alone, and not be reckoned among the nations. But now, in Christ, all are welcome to his salvation who come to him; all have equal privileges according to their faith in him, their love and devotedness to him. All that is truly valuable consists in the favour, peace, and image of God, and a life spent to his glory, in promoting the welfare of our fellow-creatures.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the remainder of this chapter the writer obtains scarcely any assistance from the earlier Scriptures, and must have drawn almost entirely from genealogical sources, accessible to him, which have since perished.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Azubah was Caleb's wife; Jerioth his concubine. He had children by both; but those of Azubah are alone recorded. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Azubah was Caleb's wife; Jerioth his concubine. He had children by both; but those of Azubah are alone recorded. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "21. Hezron … daughter of Machir the father of Gilead—that is, chief of that town, which with the lands adjacent was no doubt the property of Machir, who was so desirous of a male heir. He was grandson of Joseph. The wife of Machir was of the tribe of Manasseh (Nu 26:29).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
